Gapminder

For this assignment, we are going to use data from gapminder. Gapminder includes information about economics, population, social issues, and life expectancy from countries all over the world. We will use three data sets, so please load all three.

One thing to note is that the data include years beyond 2021. These are projections based on modeling done by the gapminder organization. Start by importing the data.

Highest

life_expectancy_tidy %>%
  filter(between(year,1920,2020)) %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarize(avg_life_exp=mean(life_expectancy)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(avg_life_exp)) %>% 
  head(n=1)

Sweden has had the highest average life expectancy over the past 100 years.

Lowest

life_expectancy_tidy %>%

              names_prefix="yr_",

  arrange(desc(delta)) %>% 
  head(n=5)

gapminder_join %>% 
  ggplot(aes(life_expectancy, y=log10(income))) +
  geom_point(shape=2, size=-.5, na.rm=T, color="blue4")+ geom_smooth(method=lm, na.rm=T, color="gold1") + theme_stata() +

## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

For this question, I wanted to do an analysis to see if there was any relationship between life expectancy and income over the past 100 years. However, upon doing the analysis, even though there appears to be a relationship, I believe that in this case correlation does not mean causation. This is because even though there is a strong positive relationship between the two variables, one does not necessarily effect the other. For example, life expectancy has increased due to the development of medications and treatments etc. but these things didnt cause an increase in income for each person. More research would have to be done to determine if these things actually contribute to each other.
